          <physDesc>
            <p>Vellum, about 11 3/4 in. by 9, consisting of 144 leaves, some of which are much stained and torn, especially foll. 1, 132â€”137, and 144. The quires, signed with both Greek (Coptic) and Syriac letters, were originally 21 in number, but of the first three only a single leaf remains, and there are lacunae of greater or less extent after foll. 20, 60, 131, 134, 135, 137, 143, and 144. From the commencement as far as fol. 121, the pages are numbered by the hand of the scribe, the verso of each leaf being marked with its appropriate letter or letters. Each page is divided into two columns, of from 29 to 34 lines.</p>
            <objectDesc form="codex">
              <supportDesc material="perg">
                <support>
                  <material>Vellum</material>
                </support>
                <extent>
                  <measure type="composition" unit="leaf" quantity="144">144 ff.</measure>
                  <dimensions type="leaf" unit="in">
                    <height>
                      <measure type="height" quantity="11.75" unit="in">11 3/4</measure>
                    </height>
                    <width>
                      <measure type="width" quantity="9" unit="in">9</measure>
                    </width>
                  </dimensions>
                </extent>
                <foliation type="ancient">From the commencement as far as<locus to="121">fol. 121</locus>, the pages are numbered by the hand of the scribe, the verso of each leaf being marked with its appropriate letter or letters</foliation>
                <collation>
                  <p>the quires signed with both Greek (Coptic) and Syriac letters were originally 21 in number but of the first three only a single leaf remains</p>
                </collation>
                <condition>
                  <list>
                    <item>
                      <p>Of 144 leaves, some are much stained and torn, especially<locus>1, 132-137, and 144</locus>; there are lacunae of greater or less extent after<locus>foll. 20, 60, 131, 134, 135, 137, 143, and 144</locus>
                      </p>
                    </item>
                  </list>
                </condition>
              </supportDesc>
              <layoutDesc>
                <layout columns="2" writtenLines="29 34">
                  <p>Each page is divided into two columns of from 29 to 34 lines</p>
                </layout>
              </layoutDesc>
            </objectDesc>
            <handDesc hands="1">
              <handNote xml:id="handNote1" scope="sole" script="syr" medium="unknown">
                <desc>This volume is written in a good, regular hand of about the xth cent.</desc>
              </handNote>
            </handDesc>
            <decoDesc>
              <decoNote xml:id="decoNote1" type="ornamentation">
                <p>This manuscript is remarkable for the ornaments and illuminations at the commencement of each discourse as well as at the top of the first and last leaves of each quire. They are executed in the Coptic style, so that the manuscript must be of Egyptian origin, and was probably written in the <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/289">Nitrian desert</placeName>.</p>
              </decoNote>
            </decoDesc>
